		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Choosing the Right: Smeagol<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.59)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223'>Joseph "Telcontar" Albers</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 6, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">   This article is the sequel (of sorts) to my Faramir article as it takes a look at the different Smeagols. Smeagol is one of the most diverse characters in the book (he debates with himself for crying out loud!) and I think that Decipher has done a good job of portraying this in the Lord of the Rings TCG. <br />
  Before I start, I want to thank everyone who constructively reviewed my Faramir article and I would like to mention a couple of points I left out. First and foremost, Wizard&#39;s Pupil is awesome in HiDaN decks! (Thanks to Starsaber and ¥LotRTCG¥!) Secondly, Ithilien Ranger is useful to start w/Greenleaf in a Roaming Fortification deck! (Thanks to Capt T.O. and Cleston!) Sorry for leaving that out guys!<br />
  So anyway, the Smeagols:<br />
<br />
1. Smeagol, Old Noser (0)<br />
   Companion<br />
   Str. 3 Vit. 4 Sig. Frodo<br />
   Ring-bound. To play, add a burden. Regroup: <br />
   Exert Smeagol (or Gollum) twice to reveal<br />
   the top 4 cards of your draw deck. Wound a<br />
   minion for each Shadow card revealed. Place<br />
   those 4 cards beneath your draw deck in any<br />
   order.<br />
<br />
Ok, many of the Smeagols are double-sided and are actually more useful to your Shadow than your Fellowship. Old Noser is one of these. Underdeeps anyone? This Smeagol can ensure that you have an automatic minion (or two or three) available each turn. He can also do this for Beren and Luthien decks. He is also an interesting form of Gollum protection as he can exert Gollum twice and then (most likely) finish him off with the revealed cards. One more deck type Old Noser could fit into is an Elven Telepathy deck w/Manager of Wizards. No Balrog in hand? Just stack normal minions on top of your deck and use Old Noser to double.<br />
<br />
2. Smeagol, Slinker (0)<br />
   Companion<br />
   Str. 3 Vit. 4 Sig. Frodo<br />
   Ring-bound. To play, add a burden. Skirmish:<br />
   Add a burden to make Smeagol strength +2 and <br />
   take no wounds.<br />
<br />
The first of the fighting Smeagols, Slinker can be a good addition to almost any deck. Had enough of Cave Trolls? Add burdens to take no wounds and, if you won, play Not Listening to heal Slinker and remove two of the added burdens! All in all, a very solid Smeagol.<br />
<br />
3. Smeagol, Poor Creature (0)<br />
   Companion<br />
   Str. 3 Vit. 4 Sig. Frodo<br />
   Ring-bound. To play, add a burden. Skirmish:<br />
   Discard a card from hand to make Smeagol <br />
   strength +1.<br />
<br />
Although he seems awesome at first, Poor Creature is not played very often. Why? Because he is really not that good. Sure, you can get an extra strength by burning cards, but he will rarely get high enough to win a skirmish (much less kill a minion). Add in Poor Wretch x 4 and he might have a chance, but that is simply using up valuable card space for a blocker. The only deck big enough for this is Moria and it will probably use Old Noser anyway. Possibly the worst of the Smeagols.<br />
<br />
4. Smeagol, Always Helps (0)<br />
   Companion<br />
   Str. 3 Vit. 4 Sig. Frodo<br />
   Ring-bound. To play, add a burden. Assignment:<br />
   Assign a minion to Smeagol and add 2 threats to<br />
   exhaust that minion.<br />
<br />
The best Smeagol, period. With Don&#39;t Look At Them, AH is a fighting MACHINE taking down the biggest and baddest for the cost of 2 threats and 3 cards. Good deal. AH does not fit into a deck, the deck fits into him. Run choke with Frodo and Sam and let AH take out the too-big baddies. Smeagol definitely does always help!<br />
<br />
5. Smeagol, Hurried Guide (0)<br />
   Companion<br />
   Str. 3 Vit. 4 Sig. Frodo<br />
   Ring-bound. To play, add a burden. Skirmish:<br />
   If you have initiative, discard 2 cards from<br />
   hand. Smeagol cannot be overwhelmed unless <br />
   his strength is tripled.<br />
<br />
Not a bad Smeagol, but Hurried Guide pales in comparison to Always Helps. He might possibly be useful if you do not have access to AH, but there are better versions out there that can do more than just survive.<br />
<br />
6. Smeagol, Slippery Sneak (0)<br />
   Companion<br />
   Str. 3 Vit. 4 Sig. Frodo<br />
   Ring-bound. To play, add a burden. Skirmish:<br />
   Add threats equal to the total vitality of <br />
   the minions Smeagol is skirmishing to discard<br />
   Smeagol. Regroup: Discard Smeagol to take a <br />
   [Gollum] minion from your discard pile into <br />
   hand. <br />
<br />
The corrupt Smeagol, Slippery Sneak is useful in a setup role for your Shelob Shadow side. Discard Smeagol and play him back repeatedly w/Master of the Precious and play Shelob on your opponent each turn! Slippery Sneak can also keep himself alive by adding threats so that he can come back and keep bringing Shelob back. He is also somewhat useful in a corruption deck to replay Gollum, Stinker as often as possible. Slippery Sneak is truly corrupt.<br />
<br />
7. Smeagol, Bearer of Great Secrets (0)<br />
   Companion<br />
   Str. 3 Vit. 4 Sig. Ringed Resistance: 7<br />
   Ring-bound. To play, add a burden. Each<br />
   time the fellowship moves, place an <br />
   unbound companion in the dead pile. <br />
   Regroup: If Smeagol is the Ring-bearer, <br />
   add 2 burdens to discard each minion.<br />
<br />
Wow! A ring-bearer Smeagol! Of course, he hasn&#39;t been released yet, but one can certainly look forward and speculate. There is really one deck type that BoGS fits into: Ring-bound Rangers! You can get around his unbound companion text and utilize his regroup ability. Add 2 burdens to BoGS and every minion will get lost in a BoG (pardon the pun) and be discarded, clearing the way for a double move. Although BoGS can be played as a normal companion, he would hurt the fellowship more than help and is really only good as your Ring-bearer. I foresee much, much potential for BoGS in the future.<br />
<br />
There you have it. The different Smeagols and their strengths and weaknesses. If I have not bored you to death or anything, I will end with my Smeagol power rankings:<br />
<br />
1. Smeagol, Always Helps<br />
2. Smeagol, Bearer of Great Secrets<br />
3. Smeagol, Old Noser<br />
4. Smeagol, Slippery Sneak<br />
5. Smeagol, Slinker<br />
6. Smeagol, Poor Creature<br />
7. Smeagol, Hurried Guide<br />
<br />
Hope you liked it!<br />
Telcontar.<br />
<br />
&quot;In the high tongue it will not sound so ill&quot;<br />
<br />
Next time, I will take a look at the versions of maybe the top companion in the game: Legolas. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=5585&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
